    "summary": "The Bandung Conference of April 1955 was a meeting of twenty-nine newly independent Asian and African nations held in Bandung, Indonesia, convened by Indonesia, India, Pakistan, Burma, and Ceylon. The conference was the first large-scale gathering of recently decolonized nations and represented an explicit assertion that Asian and African peoples would chart their own course in global affairs rather than align automatically with either Cold War superpower bloc.\n\nThe conference produced the Ten Principles of Bandung, which articulated commitments to sovereignty, non-aggression, non-interference in internal affairs, equality, and peaceful coexistence. Prominent attendees included Indian Prime Minister Jawaharlal Nehru, Chinese Premier Zhou Enlai, Egyptian President Gamal Abdel Nasser, and Indonesian President Sukarno. The conference demonstrated China's growing importance in Asian and African diplomatic affairs, with Zhou Enlai emerging as a notable figure.\n\nBandung laid the intellectual and political groundwork for the Non-Aligned Movement formally founded in Belgrade in 1961, and for the concept of a Third World or Global South as a political category distinct from the Western and Soviet blocs. Its legacy continues to influence discussions about South-South cooperation and the political agency of developing nations in global governance.",
